Text.Value: Then, after a while, I'd find whoever killed him and put a smokepowder bomb in their trousers.
Shrug.
The Ironhand Gnomes have proven the impossible. Runepowder is real. And they have it in their possession.
Now we're talking! I can whip some up for you, no problem - but I'll need a little time to gather the right supplies.
Go on.
Thank you for agreeing to find Wulbren. It means a great deal to me, indeed.
I can't risk re-capture. I barely escaped last time.
We can't count on Wulbren surviving the Towers. We should go after the gnomes en route to Baldur's Gate.
What about?
Your smokepowder bombs - are you an alchemist?
Oh, this is excellent - I'll get started right away!
It's about Wulbren. We know he's been taken to Moonrise Towers. And we know I'm going to save him.
A telepath.
I haven't been there myself. The area around it is... well. Cursed. Terrifyingly so.
I don't think you really believe that. A deep gnome strapped to a windmill wasn't your business. A group of captives suffering under mercenaries and cultists wasn't your business.
Thank you. I think I have a plan. Perhaps I can blast my way in...
What will you do if Wulbren is dead?
I'd kiss you, but neither of us deserves that.
A very fair trade, I think!
I'm certain you do. But... if you should find yourself in the Towers, perhaps you'll keep an eye out for him.
Leave.
Runepowder. Do you know what it is?
Ah, the so-called Ironhand Gnomes. Excellent access to technological facilities, but their politics are... dangerous. Increasingly so.
Perfect for thinking, and I've been doing just that.
I suppose... I suppose I'd be very, very sad.
Thank you.
I'll soon be off to gather your compensation. With your track record, I'm sure you'll find Wulbren in no time - so I'll be quick!
If you have a moment, I'd like your opinion on something.
If anything's happened to Wulbren, someone is going to be very sorry. I'll make sure of that.
Right. Wulbren's life is at stake. We must focus.
Leave.
Leave.
Honestly, I can't even remember the last time we spoke.
No matter what he's done, I can't abandon Wulbren. You understand.
Alchemist, tinkerer, adventurer, curmudgeon... I wear many hats, most with great enthusiasm.
I know you've learned about the gnomes' pursuit of runepowder. But do you know what it truly is?

EditorData.logicalname: Knows runepowder but didn't use it

Text.Value: Meanwhile, I'll need to think of an alternative. I must find Wulbren, especially now that... ahem. Anyway. Wish me luck.
That myth has come to life.
I'll let you know if I hear anything - no more, no less.
Find Wulbren, and you can have anything it is within my power to give.
Pity. Everyone deserves a friend. Even me, apparently.
That's... very decent of you. Thank you.
I don't work for free. Make me an offer.
What can you tell me about Moonrise Towers?
The stuff of gnomish myth. Gaerdal Ironhand's private cache of the world's most powerful explosive.
What do they want to do with it?
Wulbren must know their plans. And we must find him.
I... haven't that much on me, I'm afraid. But I'll tell you what: you find Wulbren, and I'll return with exactly that sum.
Good luck.
There's something else you should know. Something I can no longer ignore.
Aha! I know just the thing. You find Wulbren, and I'll gather the necessary implements.
Until very recently, I thought runepowder was a myth. A substance so powerful it could fell a city - a nation.
You'd do it, then? You'd look for him?
They've nearly started an all-out war with the Gondians in the House of Wonders in Baldur's Gate. There've been skirmishes, and now I fear...
Duergar who mentioned it sounded truly traumatised. It was almost amusing.
I did hear something interesting, though. There are shades that plague the path to the Towers - shades that fear not steel, but light.
A great deal. But I wouldn't mind halving the burden.
The problem is this: a preponderance of evidence that I am a terrible adventurer.
I'm destined for Moonrise Towers. I could look for him.
I thank you for the invitation to your camp. It's well-appointed. Not too crowded.
I've heard some rather explosive gnomish myths about it.
Pah. If only that were true. Wulbren's a good sort, but he wouldn't know his arkayas from his elbow.
You'll do it again. Won't you?
I'm hesitant to prevail upon you again. But... I can't risk re-capture. I'd be no help to Wulbren at all.
You'll give me gold. ([GEN_CheckMagicPocketGold_6057ad05-9492-4630-9f0a-be548b134c54])
Now, more than ever, I need to find him. We need to find him. He's the only one I might be able to speak to sensibly.
Barcus Wroot is my name, Baldur's Gate is my home. Back in the city, I offered my expertise to the highest bidder.
To Baldur's Gate, I expect. I don't know what they plan to do with it, but something of that power turned loose in the city... it could be carnage.
Trust me - you won't be disappointed.
The stuff of myth. Gaerdal Ironhand's private cache of the world's most powerful explosive.
I wouldn't hold out hope for any gnome taken by drow.
I wouldn't hold out hope for any gnome taken by duergar.
Perhaps that's why you've agreed to look for him. I'm lucky - and grateful.
I will.
Where have they taken it?
There's something else I'd like to discuss.
There's something else I want to discuss.
Say nothing.
What can you tell me about the gnomes you were with in the Underdark?
Destruction. The only thing it's good for. But destruction of what - well, I'm hoping Wulbren will be able to tell us.
What aren't you telling me?
Your friend can likely take care of himself.
Well. There's no point speculating. Let us leave it at 'I fear'.
Like what?
I have my own matters to attend to.
Yes, I do. Some people are worth it.
Close, are you?
Still, some bonds are simply unbreakable. Neither axe nor the ticking bomb of time can sever them.
I was quite popular too - I'm not picky about my customers.
Thank you for noticing.
Hmm. You've done so much already. I'm hesitant to prevail upon you again, but...
I'll take some more of those smokepowder bombs.
I have the feeling you're about to tell me.
Tell me a little more about yourself.
Other than a valuable explosive? Perhaps not.
I'm not sure I should trust Wulbren's fate to, well, me.
Nor I. Which means quick action is necessary.
Would you... would you look for him?
Surprise me - but make it good.
This is your business - not mine.
I shouldn't have let him drift away. Shouldn't have let that lot get their claws into him.
You saw people in need, and you helped them. It's what you do, apparently.
Change the subject.
I'll find your friend - and together, we'll stop the Ironhand Gnomes.

Synopsis: Barcus has agreed to rest in your camp. This will be his base of operations for looking for Wulbren.
